== Summary: Path from Unbearable to Bearable to Improving
<sec:summary-path>

This chapter has presented considerable detail across many symptom domains and timescales; this closing section distils it into a single narrative arc that a patient in crisis can hold in mind. The central claim is simple and deliberately hopeful: severe ME/CFS moves through recognisable stages, and the transition between them is something the patient and their care team can actively drive rather than passively await.

The subsections that follow restate that arc in three complementary forms—as a staged trajectory, as a set of key operating principles, and as a direct address to the patient. The three stages—unbearable, bearable, improving—name the trajectory from constant severe suffering, through the symptom reduction targeted by the immediate protocols (Table @tab:two-week-relief), to the gradual functional gains that fundamental treatments can produce over months to years in responders. The key messages consolidate the chapter's actionable principles: that patients can begin many interventions themselves without waiting for research trials or specialist referral, that pacing is the indispensable foundation, that a combination approach across six domains produces cumulative relief, and that reducing suffering buys the time in which new treatments continue to emerge. The final word speaks directly to the patient for whom this chapter matters most—affirming that the interventions described are available today, and that suffering can be made more bearable starting now.

